iRandom numbers play a crucial role in computing. For example, commonly		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iused SSL encryption algorithms heavily rely on random numbers. If the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irandom numbers aren't sufficiently random, attackers might potentially		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iguess them, causing the entire encryption verification system to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icollapse. However, due to the deterministic nature of computers (where		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
izero is strictly zero and one is strictly one), they cannot generate		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itruly random numbers and can only simulate randomness through complex		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ialgorithms.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOn Linux systems, leveraging its "everything is a file" philosophy,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irandom numbers generated by the Linux kernel from aggregated system		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idata can be read from `/dev/random`. But because Linux prioritizes		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isecurity and collects extensive data, the random number generation		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ispeed is very slow. This can be observed using the rngtest tool from		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe rng-tools package:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe read speed of `/dev/random` is only 361.389 Kbit/s (note: not		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ikilobytes per second). In scenarios requiring large volumes of random		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inumbers, programs are forced to wait for Linux to generate more,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icausing significant delays and stuttering.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, we often don't need such highly random numbers. The Linux		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ikernel also provides `/dev/urandom`, which uses a simpler algorithm		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand offers tens of thousands of times faster performance compared to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/dev/random`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe speed reaches 2492.940 Mbit/s—orders of magnitude faster than		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/dev/random`. But these random numbers aren't sufficiently random and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icould potentially be guessed by attackers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf software solutions can't resolve this issue, hardware can step in.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iModern motherboards typically include built-in hardware random number		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
igenerators (HRNGs), which generate random numbers using electrical		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isignals from the motherboard. Due to the high volume of data traffic,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithese electrical signals are generally unpredictable, making		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihardware-generated random numbers considered secure.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe Broadcom chipset in Raspberry Pi 3B also includes a hardware		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irandom number generator, accessible at `/dev/hwrng`. Its performance		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis as follows:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAt 1103.150 Kbit/s, it's three times faster than `/dev/random`,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isignificantly boosting performance for random-number-dependent		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iapplications. However, most programs only recognize `/dev/random` and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iignore hardware RNGs. How to address this?		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAs mentioned earlier, `/dev/random` is slow. To mitigate this, Linux		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iemploys a "randomness pool": when random numbers aren't needed, Linux		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
igradually collects entropy from system activities in the background		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand stores it in the `/dev/random` pool. During sudden high demand, it		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idraws from this pool to handle bursts without stuttering. Thus, we can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifeed random numbers from `/dev/hwrng` into the `/dev/random` pool. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inecessary tools are in the rng-tools package:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe `HRNGDEVICE` line specifies the source of supplemental		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irandomness—here we point it to the hardware RNG. Some tutorials		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isuggest setting this to `/dev/urandom`, but as noted earlier, urandom		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iisn't secure enough and would compromise system security.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIn `RNGDOPTIONS`, `--fill-watermark` replenishes the pool to the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ispecified capacity (here 50%) when entropy is low. We avoid 100%		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibecause hardware RNG implementations vary across vendors and are		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itypically undisclosed, raising concerns about potential hidden		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibackdoors. Filling to 100% implies full trust in the hardware RNG,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich could pose security risks.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`--feed-interval` sets the interval for slow replenishment after		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ireaching the target capacity; `1` is generally sufficient.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter this configuration, `/dev/random`'s random number generation		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iefficiency will improve dramatically.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}